A BinaryFunction and EvaluatableFunction that returns a (ListOfTypeFn Set_Mathematical) where the elements of each set are (quoted) instances of CycLExpression. An evaluation of an expression of the form (WNRankedHypernymDenotsForWordPOSFn_Default LEXICAL-WORD POS) function consults the WordNetKnowledgeBase WordNet_Version2_0 to find direct hypernyms of all the synsets for the LexicalWord LEXICAL-WORD based on the SpeechPart POS. A direct hypernym of the WordNetSynset BASE-SS is a more general WordNetSynset where there is an asserted, rather than implied, wnHypernym relation. Based on the LexicalWords that it finds, it will return known denotations for those hypernym words for POS. The ordering of the list is based on the assumed frequency of the meanings of the word. As its arguments indicate, this function operates to relate a LexicalWord to (possibly many) instances of CycLExpression, it does not associate instances of WordNetSynset and CycLExpression, therefore, its results will reflect the ambiguity in mapping from words to concepts. The 'default' aspect of the name indicates that this functions employs the simplest method for going from lexical words to concepts. Other functions could incorporate different available methods.

label: Marbury
WilliamMarbury
items.comment: The plaintiff in MarburyVMadison_CourtCase. He had received a judicial appointment under President JohnAdams which JohnMarshall, who was then acting as Secretary of State, failed to deliver before Adams' term expired in 1801 (Marbury's appointment, along with several others, being made literally at the eleventh hour before Adams' term expired). ThomasJefferson, when sworn in as Adams' successor, continued to withold the appointments, and Marbury petitioned the UnitedStatesSupremeCourt to compel JamesMadison, Jefferson's Secretary of State, to deliver them. The court, under the leadership of the same JohnMarshall, eventually found that Marbury's petition was misdirected in being directly addressed to the UnitedStatesSupremeCourt, inasmuch as the USConstitution only gave the court appelate jurisdiction, not original jurisdication, in such cases, so that the judicial statue under which Marbury's petition was submitted was unconstitutional. More importantly, however, this marked the first time that the UnitedStatesSupremeCourt asserted an authority, defended by Marshall in his opinion, to evaluate existing criminal and civil statutes with regard to constitutionality, i.e., the USJudicialRightToDetermineConstitutionalityOfLaw.

(VectorFromToFn OBJ1 OBJ2) may be colloquially thought of as denoting the range of directions which point from OBJ1 to OBJ2. More formally, (VectorFromToFn OBJ1 OBJ2) is a set of UnitVectorIntervals. This set, UNIT-VECTOR-SET, is constructed as follows: A set of vectors is constructed such that for every point P1 in OBJ1 and every point P2 in OBJ2 there is a vector (see Vector_Precise) with its origin at P1 and its terminus at P2. For every vector in this set, there is a parallel unit vector in UNIT-VECTOR-SET. For example, `the ball rolled towards Mecca' could be represented as (directionOfTranslation_Throughout BallRolling01 (VectorFromToFn Ball01 Mecca)). `a ball rolling away from Mecca' would be represented as (directionOfTranslation_Throughout BallRolling (VectorFromToFn Mecca Ball)). Note that the "interval" includes vectors which don't point in what is intuitively "the" direction in which the ball is rolling, since, for example, some vectors point from spots on the left side of the ball to spots on right side of Mecca. Note further that (VectorFromToFn OBJ REF) assumes that OBJ does not spatiallyIntersects REF. See also directionBetweenObjects which is roughly interchangeable with VectorFromToFn. directionBetweenObjects has the advantage that an arbitrarily precise direction may be specified. VectorFromToFn saves the user from doing the labor involved with reifying and from having to know the direction between OBJ1 and OBJ2.).

items.comment: A BinaryFunction and EvaluatableFunction that returns a Set_Mathematical of (quoted) instances of CycLExpression. An evaluation of an expression of the form (WNAllHypernymDenotsForWordPOSFn_Default LEXICAL-WORD POS) function consults the WordNetKnowledgeBase WordNet_Version2_0 to find direct hypernyms for the LexicalWord LEXICAL-WORD based on the SpeechPart POS. A direct hypernym of the WordNetSynset BASE-SS is a more general WordNetSynset where there is an asserted, rather than implied, wnHypernym relation. Based on the LexicalWords that it finds, it will return all known denotations for those hypernym words for POS. As its arguments indicate, this function operates to relate a LexicalWord to (possibly many) instances of CycLExpression. It does not associate instances of WordNetSynset and CycLExpression, therefore, its results will reflect the ambiguity in mapping from words to concepts. The 'default' aspect of the name indicates that this functions employs the simplest method for going from lexical words to concepts. Other functions could incorporate different available methods.
